## Code navigation with `repoctx`

Prefer `repoctx` over `grep`/`find`/wholesale `Read` for structural
questions about this repo. The `repoctx` skill at
`.claude/skills/repoctx/SKILL.md` carries the full command reference
and choose-the-right-tool guidance.

Quick cues:

- "Get oriented in this repo" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} overview`
- "Where is X defined?" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} definition X`
- "Show me X and its surrounding code" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} context X`
- "Explore symbols matching ..." → `{REPOCTX_BIN} symbols <substring>`
- "Find X everywhere (defs + textual, incl. comments)" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} search X`
- "Who calls X / what does X call?" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} callers X` / `{REPOCTX_BIN} callees X`
- "Trace the call chain from X" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} callgraph X --depth N --direction up|down|both`
- "What breaks if I change X?" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} impact X`
- "Find dead code / call cycles" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} deadcode` / `{REPOCTX_BIN} cycles`
- "What does this file import / what imports module M?" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} deps <file>` / `{REPOCTX_BIN} rdeps <module>`
- "Does layer A import layer B?" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} boundary --from <path> --to <module>`
- "Structure of one file" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} outline <file>`
- "Index health" → `{REPOCTX_BIN} status`

All read commands auto-index on first run. Default output is TOON for
pipes (token-efficient) and human for TTYs; pass `--json` when piping
into `jq`. Working tree: `{REPO_ROOT}`.
